article.description: Mwadi Mabika scored 17 points and Lisa Leslie added 12 to help the Los Angeles Sparks come from behind to beat the Houston Comets 59-56 Saturday night and give Michael Cooper a win in his final game before he joins the Denver Nuggets as an assistant.
article.headline: Sparks rally from 12-point deficit
article.linkText: Sparks win in Cooper's last game as coach
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Michael Cooper got a perfect sendoff.

Mwadi Mabika scored 17 points and Lisa Leslie added 12 to help
the Los Angeles Sparks come from behind to beat the Houston Comets
59-56 Saturday night and give Cooper a win in his final game before
he joins the Denver Nuggets as an assistant.

Trailing by 12 with 9:56 left in the game, the Sparks scored 13
straight points to take a 47-46 lead and never looked back.

"There was crying a little bit at the beginning of the game,
but I had to get out of that mode quick, and get into the game,"
Cooper said. "I'm going to miss all of these women. The
relationships I have with each individual one is what I am going to
miss the most, but, as I said before, this team can win a
championship with or without Michael Cooper."

The Sparks have won six straight and seven of their last eight
overall.

DeLisha Milton-Jones did not play after injuring her knee on
Friday in San Antonio. She will be reevaluated by team doctors when
the team returns to Los Angeles.

Sheryl Swoopes scored 12 points for Houston and Tina Thompson
added 10 in her first game after missing the last three weeks with
a calf strain. The Comets have lost four straight games for the
first time in franchise history and have dropped two of three at
home.

"I played hard so I don't have anything to regret," Thompson
said. "I am glad that I was just able to run up and down the
court. I wish the outcome were different. But hopefully, it will
turn out better next time."

Houston led 31-22 early in the second half, but the Sparks
responded with a 9-0 run and tied the game on a layup by Tamecka
Dixon with 16:03 to go.

"I thought we showed a lot of heart and character, especially
in the second half when we could have easily laid down," Leslie
said. "They went on some great runs but I thought we just fought
hard and played good team basketball and just found a way to win."

Houston head coach Van Chancellor said turnovers were the
difference.

"We had a 12 point lead and turned the ball over," Chancellor
said. "It's the same thing that has haunted us all year --
inappropriate turnovers at the wrong time and failure to secure the
defensive rebound."

Tiffani Johnson made a layup at 9:56 to give Houston its biggest
lead of the game, 46-34, before the Sparks rallied with a 17-1 run.

Mabika, who scored just two points in the first half, made two
shots and two free throws for six points during the run.
